  "prompt": "What are some examples of fiction written in the future tense?",
  "response": "Fiction written in the future tense is relatively rare, as most narratives are told in the past or present. However, there are a few notable examples and styles where future tense is used effectively. Here are some examples and approaches:\n\n1. **\"The Last Policeman\" by Ben H. Winters** - This novel features a world on the brink of apocalypse, and while it mainly uses past tense, there are sections that delve into expected future events that create a tense atmosphere.\n\n2. **\"Cloud Atlas\" by David Mitchell** - While this novel encompasses multiple timelines and tenses, some of its narratives employ future tense to depict events that are anticipated or imagined.\n\n3. **Speculative Fiction** - A lot of speculative fiction, particularly stories set in dystopian futures or discussing scenarios that have not yet occurred, can utilize future tense. Authors in this genre often explore what might happen with \"will\" constructions, such as \u201cIn this world, people will\u2026\u201d\n\n4. **Interactive Fiction and Choose Your Adventure stories** - These types of stories often create a sense of immediacy and anticipation by using future tense to suggest what the reader's choices will lead to.\n\n5. **Poetry and Experimental Prose** - Some poets and experimental novelists may take liberties with tense, employing the future tense to create a sense of anticipation or to explore themes of futurity.\n\n6. **\"The Light of Other Days\" by Arthur C. Clarke and Stephen Baxter** - This novel includes speculative elements that project future technologies and social structures, occasionally using future tense to describe unfolding events in this projected society.\n\nWhile these examples may not rely exclusively on future tense, they illustrate how fiction can incorporate this tense to convey anticipation, potential outcomes, or speculative plots. Future tense can serve as a unique narrative device to explore futuristic themes and concepts in a variety of literary forms.",
